[src:vue-docs/component-basics] Components allow us to split the UI into independent and reusable pieces, and think about each piece in isolation.
[src:vue-docs/component-basics] This is very similar to how we nest native HTML elements, but Vue implements its own component model that allows us to encapsulate custom content and logic in each component.
[src:vue-docs/component-basics] Vue also plays nicely with native Web Components.
[src:vue-docs/component-basics] If you are curious about the relationship between Vue Components and native Web Components, read more here.
[src:vue-docs/component-basics] The template is inlined as a JavaScript string here, which Vue will compile on the fly.
[src:vue-docs/component-basics] You can also use an ID selector pointing to an element (usually native `<template>` elements) - Vue will use its content as the template source.
[src:vue-docs/component-basics] The example above defines a single component and exports it as the default export of a `.js` file, but you can use named exports to export multiple components from the same file.
[src:vue-docs/component-basics] We will be using SFC syntax for the rest of this guide - the concepts around components are the same regardless of whether you are using a build step or not.
[src:vue-docs/component-basics] The Examples section shows component usage in both scenarios.
[src:vue-docs/component-basics] To use a child component, we need to import it in the parent component.
[src:vue-docs/component-basics] To expose the imported component to our template, we need to register it with the `components` option.
[src:vue-docs/component-basics] The component will then be available as a tag using the key it is registered under.
[src:vue-docs/component-basics] With `<script setup>`, imported components are automatically made available to the template.
[src:vue-docs/component-basics] It's also possible to globally register a component, making it available to all components in a given app without having to import it.
[src:vue-docs/component-basics] The pros and cons of global vs. local registration is discussed in the dedicated Component Registration section.
[src:vue-docs/component-basics] Notice that when clicking on the buttons, each one maintains its own, separate `count`.
[src:vue-docs/component-basics] That's because each time you use a component, a new **instance** of it is created.
[src:vue-docs/component-basics] In SFCs, it's recommended to use `PascalCase` tag names for child components to differentiate from native HTML elements.
[src:vue-docs/component-basics] Although native HTML tag names are case-insensitive, Vue SFC is a compiled format so we are able to use case-sensitive tag names in it.
[src:vue-docs/component-basics] We are also able to use `/>` to close a tag.
[src:vue-docs/component-basics] If you are authoring your templates directly in a DOM (e.g. as the content of a native `<template>` element), the template will be subject to the browser's native HTML parsing behavior.
[src:vue-docs/component-basics] See in-DOM template parsing caveats for more details.
[src:vue-docs/component-basics] If we are building a blog, we will likely need a component representing a blog post.
[src:vue-docs/component-basics] We want all the blog posts to share the same visual layout, but with different content.
[src:vue-docs/component-basics] Such a component won't be useful unless you can pass data to it, such as the title and content of the specific post we want to display.
[src:vue-docs/component-basics] Props are custom attributes you can register on a component.
[src:vue-docs/component-basics] When a value is passed to a prop attribute, it becomes a property on that component instance.
[src:vue-docs/component-basics] The value of that property is accessible within the template and on the component's `this` context, just like any other component property.
[src:vue-docs/component-basics] `defineProps` is a compile-time macro that is only available inside `<script setup>` and does not need to be explicitly imported.
[src:vue-docs/component-basics] Declared props are automatically exposed to the template.
[src:vue-docs/component-basics] A component can have as many props as you like and, by default, any value can be passed to any prop.
[src:vue-docs/component-basics] Notice how `v-bind` syntax (`:title="post.title"`) is used to pass dynamic prop values.
[src:vue-docs/component-basics] This is especially useful when you don't know the exact content you're going to render ahead of time.
[src:vue-docs/component-basics] That's all you need to know about props for now, but once you've finished reading this page and feel comfortable with its content, we recommend coming back later to read the full guide on Props.
[src:vue-docs/component-basics] As we develop our `<BlogPost>` component, some features may require communicating back up to the parent.
[src:vue-docs/component-basics] For example, we may decide to include an accessibility feature to enlarge the text of blog posts, while leaving the rest of the page at its default size.
[src:vue-docs/component-basics] The button doesn't do anything yet - we want clicking the button to communicate to the parent that it should enlarge the text of all posts.
[src:vue-docs/component-basics] To solve this problem, components provide a custom events system.
[src:vue-docs/component-basics] Thanks to the `@enlarge-text="postFontSize += 0.1"` listener, the parent will receive the event and update the value of `postFontSize`.
[src:vue-docs/component-basics] This documents all the events that a component emits and optionally validates them.
[src:vue-docs/component-basics] It also allows Vue to avoid implicitly applying them as native listeners to the child component's root element.
[src:vue-docs/component-basics] Similar to `defineProps`, `defineEmits` is only usable in `<script setup>` and doesn't need to be imported.
[src:vue-docs/component-basics] It returns an `emit` function that is equivalent to the `$emit` method.
[src:vue-docs/component-basics] If you are not using `<script setup>`, you can declare emitted events using the `emits` option.
[src:vue-docs/component-basics] That's all you need to know about custom component events for now, but once you've finished reading this page and feel comfortable with its content, we recommend coming back later to read the full guide on Custom Events.
[src:vue-docs/component-basics] As you'll see above, we use the `<slot>` as a placeholder where we want the content to go – and that's it.
[src:vue-docs/component-basics] That's all you need to know about slots for now, but once you've finished reading this page and feel comfortable with its content, we recommend coming back later to read the full guide on Slots.
[src:vue-docs/component-basics] You can also use the `is` attribute to create regular HTML elements.
[src:vue-docs/component-basics] When switching between multiple components with `<component :is="...">`, a component will be unmounted when it is switched away from.
[src:vue-docs/component-basics] We can force the inactive components to stay "alive" with the built-in `<KeepAlive>` component.
[src:vue-docs/component-basics] If you are writing your Vue templates directly in the DOM, Vue will have to retrieve the template string from the DOM.
[src:vue-docs/component-basics] This leads to some caveats due to browsers' native HTML parsing behavior.
[src:vue-docs/component-basics] It should be noted that the limitations discussed below only apply if you are writing your templates directly in the DOM.
[src:vue-docs/component-basics] HTML tags and attribute names are case-insensitive, so browsers will interpret any uppercase characters as lowercase.
[src:vue-docs/component-basics] This is because Vue's template parser respects `/>` as an indication to end any tag, regardless of its type.
[src:vue-docs/component-basics] This is because the HTML spec only allows a few specific elements to omit closing tags, the most common being `<input>` and `<img>`.
[src:vue-docs/component-basics] For all other elements, if you omit the closing tag, the native HTML parser will think you never terminated the opening tag.
[src:vue-docs/component-basics] Some HTML elements, such as `<ul>`, `<ol>`, `<table>` and `<select>` have restrictions on what elements can appear inside them, and some elements such as `<li>`, `<tr>`, and `<option>` can only appear inside certain other elements.
[src:vue-docs/component-basics] This will lead to issues when using components with elements that have such restrictions.
[src:vue-docs/component-basics] The custom component `<blog-post-row>` will be hoisted out as invalid content, causing errors in the eventual rendered output.
[src:vue-docs/component-basics] When used on native HTML elements, the value of `is` must be prefixed with `vue:` in order to be interpreted as a Vue component.
[src:vue-docs/component-basics] This is required to avoid confusion with native customized built-in elements.
[src:vue-docs/component-basics] That's all you need to know about in-DOM template parsing caveats for now - and actually, the end of Vue's *Essentials*.
[src:vue-docs/component-basics] There's still more to learn, but first, we recommend taking a break to play with Vue yourself - build something fun, or check out some of the Examples if you haven't already.
[src:vue-docs/component-basics] Once you feel comfortable with the knowledge you've just digested, move on with the guide to learn more about components in depth.
[src:vue-docs/components-props] Vue components require explicit props declaration so that Vue knows what external props passed to the component should be treated as fallthrough attributes (which will be discussed in its dedicated section).
[src:vue-docs/components-props] Notice the argument passed to `defineProps()` is the same as the value provided to the `props` options: the same props options API is shared between the two declaration styles.
[src:vue-docs/components-props] For each property in the object declaration syntax, the key is the name of the prop, while the value should be the constructor function of the expected type.
[src:vue-docs/components-props] This not only documents your component, but will also warn other developers using your component in the browser console if they pass the wrong type.
[src:vue-docs/components-props] We will discuss more details about prop validation further down this page.
[src:vue-docs/components-props] Vue's reactivity system tracks state usage based on property access.
[src:vue-docs/components-props] E.g. when you access `props.foo` in a computed getter or a watcher, the `foo` prop gets tracked as a dependency.
[src:vue-docs/components-props] In version 3.4 and below, `foo` is an actual constant and will never change.
[src:vue-docs/components-props] In version 3.5 and above, Vue's compiler automatically prepends `props.` when code in the same `<script setup>` block accesses variables destructured from `defineProps`.
[src:vue-docs/components-props] In addition, you can use JavaScript's native default value syntax to declare default values for the props.
[src:vue-docs/components-props] If you prefer to have more visual distinction between destructured props and normal variables in your IDE, Vue's VSCode extension provides a setting to enable inlay-hints for destructured props.
[src:vue-docs/components-props] This will not work as expected because it is equivalent to `watch(props.foo, ...)` - we are passing a value instead of a reactive data source to `watch`.
[src:vue-docs/components-props] In fact, Vue's compiler will catch such cases and throw a warning.
[src:vue-docs/components-props] The external function can call the getter (or normalize it with toValue) when it needs to track changes of the provided prop, e.g. in a computed or watcher getter.
[src:vue-docs/components-props] Technically, you can also use camelCase when passing props to a child component (except in in-DOM templates).
[src:vue-docs/components-props] We use PascalCase for component tags when possible because it improves template readability by differentiating Vue components from native elements.
[src:vue-docs/components-props] However, there isn't as much practical benefit in using camelCase when passing props, so we choose to follow each language's conventions.
[src:vue-docs/components-props] In the two examples above, we happen to pass string values, but *any* type of value can be passed to a prop.
[src:vue-docs/components-props] If you want to pass all the properties of an object as props, you can use `v-bind` without an argument (`v-bind` instead of `:prop-name`).
[src:vue-docs/components-props] When `v-bind` is used alongside explicit bindings on the same component, Vue internally calls `mergeProps()` to combine them.
[src:vue-docs/components-props] The full merging rules are described in the `mergeProps()` API reference.
[src:vue-docs/components-props] All props form a **one-way-down binding** between the child property and the parent one: when the parent property updates, it will flow down to the child, but not the other way around.
[src:vue-docs/components-props] This prevents child components from accidentally mutating the parent's state, which can make your app's data flow harder to understand.
[src:vue-docs/components-props] In addition, every time the parent component is updated, all props in the child component will be refreshed with the latest value.
[src:vue-docs/components-props] This means you should **not** attempt to mutate a prop inside a child component.
[src:vue-docs/components-props] When objects and arrays are passed as props, while the child component cannot mutate the prop binding, it **will** be able to mutate the object or array's nested properties.
[src:vue-docs/components-props] This is because in JavaScript objects and arrays are passed by reference, and it is unreasonably expensive for Vue to prevent such mutations.
[src:vue-docs/components-props] The main drawback of such mutations is that it allows the child component to affect parent state in a way that isn't obvious to the parent component, potentially making it more difficult to reason about the data flow in the future.
[src:vue-docs/components-props] As a best practice, you should avoid such mutations unless the parent and child are tightly coupled by design.
[src:vue-docs/components-props] In most cases, the child should emit an event to let the parent perform the mutation.
[src:vue-docs/components-props] Components can specify requirements for their props, such as the types you've already seen.
[src:vue-docs/components-props] If a requirement is not met, Vue will warn you in the browser's JavaScript console.
[src:vue-docs/components-props] This is especially useful when developing a component that is intended to be used by others.
[src:vue-docs/components-props] To specify prop validations, you can provide an object with validation requirements to the `defineProps()` macro`props` option, instead of an array of strings.
[src:vue-docs/components-props] Code inside the `defineProps()` argument **cannot access other variables declared in `<script setup>`**, because the entire expression is moved to an outer function scope when compiled.
[src:vue-docs/components-props] When prop validation fails, Vue will produce a console warning (if using the development build).
[src:vue-docs/components-props] If using Type-based props declarations , Vue will try its best to compile the type annotations into equivalent runtime prop declarations.
[src:vue-docs/components-props] For example, `defineProps<{ msg: string }>` will be compiled into `{ msg: { type: String, required: true }}`.
[src:vue-docs/components-props] Note that props are validated **before** a component instance is created, so instance properties (e.g.
[src:vue-docs/components-props] `data`, `computed`, etc.) will not be available inside `default` or `validator` functions.
[src:vue-docs/components-props] In addition, `type` can also be a custom class or constructor function and the assertion will be made with an `instanceof` check.
[src:vue-docs/components-props] Vue will use `instanceof Person` to validate whether the value of the `author` prop is indeed an instance of the `Person` class.
[src:vue-docs/components-props] Note that if `type` is just `null` without using the array syntax, it will allow any type.
[src:vue-docs/components-props] Props with `Boolean` type have special casting rules to mimic the behavior of native boolean attributes.
[src:vue-docs/components-props] When a prop is declared to allow multiple types, the casting rules for `Boolean` will also be applied.
[src:vue-docs/introduction] You are reading the documentation for Vue 3!
[src:vue-docs/introduction] Vue (pronounced /vjuː/, like **view**) is a JavaScript framework for building user interfaces.
[src:vue-docs/introduction] It builds on top of standard HTML, CSS, and JavaScript and provides a declarative, component-based programming model that helps you efficiently develop user interfaces of any complexity.
[src:vue-docs/introduction] You may already have questions - don't worry.
[src:vue-docs/introduction] We will cover every little detail in the rest of the documentation.
[src:vue-docs/introduction] For now, please read along so you can have a high-level understanding of what Vue offers.
[src:vue-docs/introduction] The rest of the documentation assumes basic familiarity with HTML, CSS, and JavaScript.
[src:vue-docs/introduction] If you are totally new to frontend development, it might not be the best idea to jump right into a framework as your first step - grasp the basics and then come back!
[src:vue-docs/introduction] You can check your knowledge level with these overviews for JavaScript, HTML and CSS if needed.
[src:vue-docs/introduction] Prior experience with other frameworks helps, but is not required.
[src:vue-docs/introduction] Vue is a framework and ecosystem that covers most of the common features needed in frontend development.
[src:vue-docs/introduction] But the web is extremely diverse - the things we build on the web may vary drastically in form and scale.
[src:vue-docs/introduction] With that in mind, Vue is designed to be flexible and incrementally adoptable.
[src:vue-docs/introduction] If you find these concepts intimidating, don't worry!
[src:vue-docs/introduction] The tutorial and guide only require basic HTML and JavaScript knowledge, and you should be able to follow along without being an expert in any of these.
[src:vue-docs/introduction] If you are an experienced developer interested in how to best integrate Vue into your stack, or you are curious about what these terms mean, we discuss them in more detail in Ways of Using Vue.
[src:vue-docs/introduction] Despite the flexibility, the core knowledge about how Vue works is shared across all these use cases.
[src:vue-docs/introduction] Even if you are just a beginner now, the knowledge gained along the way will stay useful as you grow to tackle more ambitious goals in the future.
[src:vue-docs/introduction] If you are a veteran, you can pick the optimal way to leverage Vue based on the problems you are trying to solve, while retaining the same productivity.
[src:vue-docs/introduction] This is why we call Vue "The Progressive Framework": it's a framework that can grow with you and adapt to your needs.
[src:vue-docs/introduction] In most build-tool-enabled Vue projects, we author Vue components using an HTML-like file format called **Single-File Component** (also known as `*.vue` files, abbreviated as **SFC**).
[src:vue-docs/introduction] A Vue SFC, as the name suggests, encapsulates the component's logic (JavaScript), template (HTML), and styles (CSS) in a single file.
[src:vue-docs/introduction] SFC is a defining feature of Vue and is the recommended way to author Vue components **if** your use case warrants a build setup.
[src:vue-docs/introduction] You can learn more about the how and why of SFC in its dedicated section - but for now, just know that Vue will handle all the build tools setup for you.
[src:vue-docs/introduction] Vue components can be authored in two different API styles: **Options API** and **Composition API**.
[src:vue-docs/introduction] With Options API, we define a component's logic using an object of options such as `data`, `methods`, and `mounted`.
[src:vue-docs/introduction] With Composition API, we define a component's logic using imported API functions.
[src:vue-docs/introduction] In SFCs, Composition API is typically used with `<script setup>`.
[src:vue-docs/introduction] The `setup` attribute is a hint that makes Vue perform compile-time transforms that allow us to use Composition API with less boilerplate.
[src:vue-docs/introduction] For example, imports and top-level variables / functions declared in `<script setup>` are directly usable in the template.
[src:vue-docs/introduction] Both API styles are fully capable of covering common use cases.
[src:vue-docs/introduction] They are different interfaces powered by the exact same underlying system.
[src:vue-docs/introduction] In fact, the Options API is implemented on top of the Composition API!
[src:vue-docs/introduction] The fundamental concepts and knowledge about Vue are shared across the two styles.
[src:vue-docs/introduction] The Options API is centered around the concept of a "component instance" (`this` as seen in the example), which typically aligns better with a class-based mental model for users coming from OOP language backgrounds.
[src:vue-docs/introduction] It is also more beginner-friendly by abstracting away the reactivity details and enforcing code organization via option groups.
[src:vue-docs/introduction] The Composition API is centered around declaring reactive state variables directly in a function scope and composing state from multiple functions together to handle complexity.
[src:vue-docs/introduction] It is more free-form and requires an understanding of how reactivity works in Vue to be used effectively.
[src:vue-docs/introduction] In return, its flexibility enables more powerful patterns for organizing and reusing logic.
[src:vue-docs/introduction] You can learn more about the comparison between the two styles and the potential benefits of Composition API in the Composition API FAQ.
[src:vue-docs/introduction] You don't have to commit to only one style during the learning phase.
[src:vue-docs/introduction] The rest of the documentation will provide code samples in both styles where applicable, and you can toggle between them at any time using the **API Preference switches** at the top of the left sidebar.
[src:vue-docs/introduction] Different developers have different learning styles.
[src:vue-docs/introduction] Feel free to pick a learning path that suits your preference - although we do recommend going over all of the content, if possible!
[src:vue-docs/introduction] For those who prefer learning things hands-on.
[src:vue-docs/introduction] The guide walks you through every aspect of the framework in full detail.
[src:vue-docs/introduction] Explore examples of core features and common UI tasks.
[src:vue-docs/reactivity-fundamentals] This page and many other chapters later in the guide contain different content for the Options API and the Composition API.
[src:vue-docs/reactivity-fundamentals] Your current preference is Options APIComposition API.
[src:vue-docs/reactivity-fundamentals] You can toggle between the API styles using the "API Preference" switches at the top of the left sidebar.
[src:vue-docs/reactivity-fundamentals] With the Options API, we use the `data` option to declare reactive state of a component.
[src:vue-docs/reactivity-fundamentals] The option value should be a function that returns an object.
[src:vue-docs/reactivity-fundamentals] Vue will call the function when creating a new component instance, and wrap the returned object in its reactivity system.
[src:vue-docs/reactivity-fundamentals] These instance properties are only added when the instance is first created, so you need to ensure they are all present in the object returned by the `data` function.
[src:vue-docs/reactivity-fundamentals] Where necessary, use `null`, `undefined` or some other placeholder value for properties where the desired value isn't yet available.
[src:vue-docs/reactivity-fundamentals] It is possible to add a new property directly to `this` without including it in `data`.
[src:vue-docs/reactivity-fundamentals] However, properties added this way will not be able to trigger reactive updates.
[src:vue-docs/reactivity-fundamentals] Vue uses a `$` prefix when exposing its own built-in APIs via the component instance.
[src:vue-docs/reactivity-fundamentals] It also reserves the prefix `_` for internal properties.
[src:vue-docs/reactivity-fundamentals] You should avoid using names for top-level `data` properties that start with either of these characters.
[src:vue-docs/reactivity-fundamentals] In Vue 3, data is made reactive by leveraging JavaScript Proxies.
[src:vue-docs/reactivity-fundamentals] When you access `this.someObject` after assigning it, the value is a reactive proxy of the original `newObject`.
[src:vue-docs/reactivity-fundamentals] Notice that we did **not** need to append `.value` when using the ref in the template.
[src:vue-docs/reactivity-fundamentals] For convenience, refs are automatically unwrapped when used inside templates (with a few caveats).
[src:vue-docs/reactivity-fundamentals] Here's the example live on Codepen, without using any build tools.
[src:vue-docs/reactivity-fundamentals] Manually exposing state and methods via `setup()` can be verbose.
[src:vue-docs/reactivity-fundamentals] Luckily, it can be avoided when using Single-File Components (SFCs).
[src:vue-docs/reactivity-fundamentals] Top-level imports, variables and functions declared in `<script setup>` are automatically usable in the template of the same component.
[src:vue-docs/reactivity-fundamentals] Think of the template as a JavaScript function declared in the same scope - it naturally has access to everything declared alongside it.
[src:vue-docs/reactivity-fundamentals] For the rest of the guide, we will be primarily using SFC + `<script setup>` syntax for the Composition API code examples, as that is the most common usage for Vue developers.
[src:vue-docs/reactivity-fundamentals] If you are not using SFC, you can still use Composition API with the `setup()` option.
[src:vue-docs/reactivity-fundamentals] You might be wondering why we need refs with the `.value` instead of plain variables.
[src:vue-docs/reactivity-fundamentals] To explain that, we will need to briefly discuss how Vue's reactivity system works.
[src:vue-docs/reactivity-fundamentals] When you use a ref in a template, and change the ref's value later, Vue automatically detects the change and updates the DOM accordingly.
[src:vue-docs/reactivity-fundamentals] This is made possible with a dependency-tracking based reactivity system.
[src:vue-docs/reactivity-fundamentals] When a component is rendered for the first time, Vue **tracks** every ref that was used during the render.
[src:vue-docs/reactivity-fundamentals] Later on, when a ref is mutated, it will **trigger** a re-render for components that are tracking it.
[src:vue-docs/reactivity-fundamentals] In standard JavaScript, there is no way to detect the access or mutation of plain variables.
[src:vue-docs/reactivity-fundamentals] However, we can intercept the get and set operations of an object's properties using getter and setter methods.
[src:vue-docs/reactivity-fundamentals] The `.value` property gives Vue the opportunity to detect when a ref has been accessed or mutated.
[src:vue-docs/reactivity-fundamentals] Under the hood, Vue performs the tracking in its getter, and performs triggering in its setter.
[src:vue-docs/reactivity-fundamentals] Another nice trait of refs is that unlike plain variables, you can pass refs into functions while retaining access to the latest value and the reactivity connection.
[src:vue-docs/reactivity-fundamentals] This is particularly useful when refactoring complex logic into reusable code.
[src:vue-docs/reactivity-fundamentals] The reactivity system is discussed in more details in the Reactivity in Depth section.
[src:vue-docs/reactivity-fundamentals] To add methods to a component instance we use the `methods` option.
[src:vue-docs/reactivity-fundamentals] Vue automatically binds the `this` value for `methods` so that it always refers to the component instance.
[src:vue-docs/reactivity-fundamentals] This ensures that a method retains the correct `this` value if it's used as an event listener or callback.
[src:vue-docs/reactivity-fundamentals] Just like all other properties of the component instance, the `methods` are accessible from within the component's template.
[src:vue-docs/reactivity-fundamentals] In the example above, the method `increment` will be called when the `<button>` is clicked.
[src:vue-docs/reactivity-fundamentals] In Vue, state is deeply reactive by default.
[src:vue-docs/reactivity-fundamentals] Refs can hold any value type, including deeply nested objects, arrays, or JavaScript built-in data structures like `Map`.
[src:vue-docs/reactivity-fundamentals] A ref will make its value deeply reactive.
[src:vue-docs/reactivity-fundamentals] Non-primitive values are turned into reactive proxies via `reactive()`, which is discussed below.
[src:vue-docs/reactivity-fundamentals] It is also possible to opt-out of deep reactivity with shallow refs.
[src:vue-docs/reactivity-fundamentals] For shallow refs, only `.value` access is tracked for reactivity.
[src:vue-docs/reactivity-fundamentals] Shallow refs can be used for optimizing performance by avoiding the observation cost of large objects, or in cases where the inner state is managed by an external library.
[src:vue-docs/reactivity-fundamentals] When you mutate reactive state, the DOM is updated automatically.
[src:vue-docs/reactivity-fundamentals] However, it should be noted that the DOM updates are not applied synchronously.
[src:vue-docs/reactivity-fundamentals] Instead, Vue buffers them until the "next tick" in the update cycle to ensure that each component updates only once no matter how many state changes you have made.
[src:vue-docs/reactivity-fundamentals] There is another way to declare reactive state, with the `reactive()` API.
[src:vue-docs/reactivity-fundamentals] Reactive objects are JavaScript Proxies and behave just like normal objects.
[src:vue-docs/reactivity-fundamentals] The difference is that Vue is able to intercept the access and mutation of all properties of a reactive object for reactivity tracking and triggering.
[src:vue-docs/reactivity-fundamentals] `reactive()` converts the object deeply: nested objects are also wrapped with `reactive()` when accessed.
[src:vue-docs/reactivity-fundamentals] It is also called by `ref()` internally when the ref value is an object.
[src:vue-docs/reactivity-fundamentals] Similar to shallow refs, there is also the `shallowReactive()` API for opting-out of deep reactivity.
[src:vue-docs/reactivity-fundamentals] Only the proxy is reactive - mutating the original object will not trigger updates.
[src:vue-docs/reactivity-fundamentals] Therefore, the best practice when working with Vue's reactivity system is to **exclusively use the proxied versions of your state**.
[src:vue-docs/reactivity-fundamentals] This rule applies to nested objects as well.
[src:vue-docs/reactivity-fundamentals] **Cannot replace entire object:** since Vue's reactivity tracking works over property access, we must always keep the same reference to the reactive object.
[src:vue-docs/reactivity-fundamentals] Due to these limitations, we recommend using `ref()` as the primary API for declaring reactive state.
[src:vue-docs/reactivity-fundamentals] A ref is automatically unwrapped when accessed or mutated as a property of a reactive object.
[src:vue-docs/reactivity-fundamentals] Ref unwrapping only happens when nested inside a deep reactive object.
[src:vue-docs/reactivity-fundamentals] It does not apply when it is accessed as a property of a shallow reactive object.
[src:vue-docs/reactivity-fundamentals] Ref unwrapping in templates only applies if the ref is a top-level property in the template render context.
[src:vue-docs/reactivity-fundamentals] The rendered result will be `[object Object]1` because `object.id` is not unwrapped when evaluating the expression and remains a ref object.
[src:vue-docs/reactivity-fundamentals] This is just a convenience feature of text interpolation and is equivalent to `{{ object.id.value }}`.
[src:vue-docs/reactivity-fundamentals] However, this approach is problematic for components that are reused because a debounced function is **stateful**: it maintains some internal state on the elapsed time.
[src:vue-docs/reactivity-fundamentals] If multiple component instances share the same debounced function, they will interfere with one another.
